  {
    "name": "listTables",
    "title": "List Tables",
    "description": "List tables in a database, optionally filtered and/or with full metadata.\n\n<usecase>\nUse when:\n- Exploring a database to find relevant tables (brief mode, default).\n- Searching for a table by partial name (pass `search`).\n- Inspecting a table's columns, constraints, indexes, and triggers before writing a query (pass `detailed: true`). This supersedes the legacy `getTableSchema` tool.\n</usecase>\n\n<parameters>\n- `database` â€” Database to target. Defaults to the active database.\n- `cursor` â€” Opaque pagination cursor; echo the prior response's `nextCursor`.\n- `search` â€” Case-insensitive filter on table names via `ILIKE`. `%` matches any sequence; `_` matches a single character.\n- `detailed` â€” When `true`, returns full metadata objects keyed by table name instead of bare name strings. Default `false`.\n</parameters>\n\n<examples>\nâś“ \"What tables are in mydb?\" â†’ listTables(database=\"mydb\")\nâś“ \"Find the orders table\" â†’ listTables(search=\"order\")\nâś“ \"What columns does orders have?\" â†’ listTables(search=\"orders\", detailed=true)\n</examples>\n\n<what_it_returns>\nBrief mode (default): a sorted JSON array of table-name strings, e.g. `[\"customers\", \"orders\"]`.\nDetailed mode: a JSON object keyed by table name; each value carries `schema`, `kind`, `owner`, `comment`, `columns`, `constraints`, `indexes`, and `triggers` (the name is the key and is not repeated inside the value). Keys iterate in the same alphabetical order brief mode uses. Example: `{\"orders\": {\"schema\": \"public\", \"kind\": \"TABLE\", â€¦}}`.\n</what_it_returns>\n\n<pagination>\nPaginated. Pass the prior response's `nextCursor` as `cursor` to fetch the next page. The `search` filter must stay the same across pages for cursor continuity.\n</pagination>",
    "inputSchema": {
      "$schema": "https://json-schema.org/draft/2020-12/schema",
      "description": "Request for the Postgres `listTables` tool â€” extends the shared shape with `search` and `detailed`.",
      "properties": {
        "cursor": {
          "default": null,
          "description": "Opaque cursor from a prior response's `nextCursor`; omit for the first page.",
          "type": [
            "string",
            "null"
          ]
        },
        "database": {
          "default": null,
          "description": "Database to list tables from. Defaults to the active database.",
          "type": [
            "string",
            "null"
          ]
        },
        "detailed": {
          "default": false,
          "description": "When `true`, each returned entry is a full metadata object (columns,\nconstraints, indexes, triggers, owner, comment, kind); when `false` or\nomitted, each entry is the bare table-name string.",
          "type": "boolean"
        },
        "search": {
          "default": null,
          "description": "Optional case-insensitive filter on table names. The input is used within an `ILIKE`\nclause: `%` matches any sequence of characters and `_` matches any single character.",
          "type": [
            "string",
            "null"
          ]
        }
      },
      "title": "ListTablesRequest",
      "type": "object"
    },
    "outputSchema": {
      "$defs": {
        "TableEntries": {
          "anyOf": [
            {
              "description": "Brief mode: sorted array of bare table-name strings.",
              "items": {
                "type": "string"
              },
              "type": "array"
            },
            {
              "additionalProperties": true,
              "description": "Detailed mode: name-keyed map; insertion order matches the SQL `ORDER BY` sort.",
              "type": "object"
            }
          ],
          "description": "Two-shape table listing payload: bare names in brief mode, name-keyed map in detailed mode.\n\nChosen by the handler based on [`ListTablesRequest::detailed`]. Serialises untagged: brief\nmode becomes a JSON array of strings, detailed mode becomes a JSON object whose keys are\ntable names and whose values are the per-table metadata."
        }
      },
      "$schema": "https://json-schema.org/draft/2020-12/schema",
      "description": "Response for the `listTables` tool.",
      "properties": {
        "nextCursor": {
          "description": "Opaque cursor pointing to the next page. Absent when this is the final page.",
          "type": [
            "string",
            "null"
          ]
        },
        "tables": {
          "$ref": "#/$defs/TableEntries",
          "description": "Page of matching tables. Shape depends on the request's `detailed` flag."
        }
      },
      "required": [
        "tables"
      ],
      "title": "ListTablesResponse",
      "type": "object"
    },
    "annotations": {
      "readOnlyHint": true,
      "destructiveHint": false,
      "idempotentHint": true,
      "openWorldHint": false
    }
  },
  {
    "name": "listTriggers",
    "title": "List Triggers",
    "description": "List all user-defined triggers on tables in the `public` schema of a database. Internal constraint and foreign-key triggers are excluded.\n\n<usecase>\nUse when:\n- Investigating side-effects on INSERT/UPDATE/DELETE for a table\n- Auditing trigger coverage across a database\n- The user asks what triggers fire in a database\n</usecase>\n\n<examples>\nâś“ \"What triggers are in the mydb database?\" â†’ listTriggers(database=\"mydb\")\nâś“ \"Does an order-audit trigger exist?\" â†’ listTriggers to check\nâś— \"Show me a trigger's body\" â†’ use readQuery against pg_trigger or information_schema.triggers\n</examples>\n\n<what_it_returns>\nA sorted JSON array of trigger name strings.\n</what_it_returns>\n\n<pagination>\nPaginated. Pass the prior response's `nextCursor` as `cursor` to fetch the next page.\n</pagination>",
